# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aaron-manby
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby-ironmaster] Manby was born at Albrighton, Shropshire on 15 November 1776 to Aaron Manby of Kingston, Jamaica and Jane Lane of Bentley.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby-ironmaster] They had a son, Charles Manby, who became Secretary of the Institution of Civil Engineers.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1807 Manby married Sarah Ann Haskins, with whom he had one daughter, Sarah Maria (d.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby-ironmaster] The oldest three of them, John Richard (1813-1869), Joseph Lane (1814-1862), and Edward Oliver (1816-1864), also became civil engineers.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby-ironmaster] Manby's working life was originally in banks on the Isle of Wight.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1812 Manby was managing partner of the Horseley Coal and Iron Co, Tipton, Staffordshire.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby-ironmaster] It ran coal mines, blast furnaces to make iron, and assorted workshops.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby-ironmaster] Manby expanded the business into civil engineering.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1813 Manby obtained patent No 3705 for a means of casting the slag from blast furnaces into blocks for building.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1815, the firm supplied a cast-iron swing bridge, possibly the first of Horseley's many iron bridges.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1821, diversifying into mechanical engineering, Manby obtained British Patent No 4558 for his "oscillating engine" designed for use in ships.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby-ironmaster] That same year, Horseley Ironworks constructed the world's first seagoing iron steamboat, named the *Aaron Manby*, using his oscillating engine.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby-ironmaster] The boat was built at Tipton using temporary bolts, disassembled for transportation to London, and reassembled on the Thames in 1822, this time using permanent rivets.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby-ironmaster] Between 1819 and 1822, Manby started his engineering works at Charenton-le-Pont, near Paris, with the Scottish chemist Daniel Wilson as manager.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby-ironmaster] This controversial move enabled France to stop buying engines made in England, which made Manby somewhat unpopular.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1822 Manby and Wilson's *Compagnie d'Éclairage par de Gaz Hydrogène* ('Hydrogen Gas Lighting Company') was granted the right to provide gas lighting for several streets in Paris.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby-ironmaster] According to Michel Cotte, "The company Manby & Wilson is certainly the largest company of British origin which set up in France under the Restoration." Their *"Compagnie Anglaise"* ran until 1847, expanding to take in the Le Creusot ironworks.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby-ironmaster] Manby's Horseley Ironworks profited from the growing canal trade, manufacturing canal bridges in the English Midlands including the Engine Arm Aqueduct (1825) and two roving bridges at Smethwick Junction (1828).
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1845 Manby sold Horseley Ironworks to John Joseph Bramah (~1798 - 1846), nephew of the inventor and locksmith Joseph Bramah.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby-ironmaster] After returning from France in about 1840, he lived at Fulham, London, before retiring to the Isle of Wight where he died.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby] Launched in 1821, *Aaron Manby* was the first steamship to be built of iron.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby] She was the brainchild of the eccentric but far-seeing naval officer Captain (later Admiral) Charles Napier, who had conceived the idea of a fleet of steamships for service on the River Seine.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby] The ship was named after the master of the Horseley Ironworks, Tipton, Staffordshire, where she was pre-fabricated to a design jointly formulated by Captain Napier, Aaron Manby and his son Charles.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby] She was then shipped in pieces to Rotherhithe on the Thames and assembled there.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby] Of 116 tons burthen, the ship was 120 feet (37 m) long.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby] Her flat-bottomed hull was made of 1⁄4-inch-thick (6.4 mm) iron plate fastened to angle-iron ribs.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby] There was one deck, of wood, and a bowsprit.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby] The ship's distinctive profile boasted a single 47-foot-high (14 m) funnel.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby] The engine was of the oscillating type, designed and patented (British Patent No 4558 of 1821) by Aaron Manby.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby] The paddlewheels: were 12 feet (3.7 m) in diameter but only 2.5 feet (76 cm) wide, because the vessel's maximum beam was limited to 23 feet (7.0 m) for service on the Seine.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby] Defying the prevailing wisdom of the day, the iron-hulled vessel not only floated but made 9 knots (10 mph; 17 km/h) and drew one foot (30 cm) less water than any other steamboat then operating.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby] After trials in May 1822, *Aaron Manby* crossed the English Channel to Le Havre under Napier's command on 10 June, at an average speed of 8 knots (9.2 mph; 15 km/h), carrying passengers and freighted with a cargo of linseed and iron castings.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby] The ship proceeded up the Seine to Paris, where she caused a great stir and where she was based for the next decade.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby] This has been claimed (incorrectly) as the first passage from Britain to France by steam ship.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby] There had been shorter crossings by wooden steamers, but Napier's was the first direct steam crossing from London to Paris and the first seagoing voyage by an iron ship anywhere.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby] After some further channel voyages the ship was used for pleasure trips up and down the Seine.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby] The use of iron plates for the hull, in place of wood, was widely copied in shipbuilding during the following decades.
[src:aaron-manby/aaron-manby] Napier had conceived the ship as a first step towards an iron warship, and in this sense *Aaron Manby* could be considered a direct ancestor of the Royal Navy's first iron frigate, HMS *Warrior*, built the year of Napier's death.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Bankrupt is not the only legal status that an insolvent person may have, meaning the term *bankruptcy* is not a synonym for insolvency.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The word *bankruptcy* is derived from Italian *banca rotta*, literally meaning 'broken bank'.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The term is often described as having originated in Renaissance Italy, where there allegedly existed the tradition of smashing a banker's bench if he defaulted on payment.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] However, the existence of such a ritual is doubted.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In Ancient Greece, bankruptcy did not exist.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] If a man owed and he could not pay, he and his wife, children or servants were forced into "debt slavery" until the creditor recouped losses through their physical labour.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Many city-states in ancient Greece limited debt slavery to a period of five years; debt slaves had protection of life and limb, which regular slaves did not have.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] However, servants of the debtor could be retained beyond that deadline by the creditor and were often forced to serve their new lord for a lifetime, usually under significantly harsher conditions.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] An exception to this rule was Athens, which by the laws of Solon forbade enslavement for debt; as a consequence, most Athenian slaves were foreigners (Greek or otherwise).
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The Statute of Bankrupts of 1542 was the first statute under English law dealing with bankruptcy or insolvency.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Bankruptcy is also documented in East Asia.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] According to al-Maqrizi, the Yassa of Genghis Khan contained a provision that mandated the death penalty for anyone who became bankrupt three times.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] A failure of a nation to meet bond repayments has been seen on many occasions.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In a similar way, Philip II of Spain had to declare four state bankruptcies in 1557, 1560, 1575 and 1596.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Rogoff, "Although the development of international capital markets was quite limited prior to 1800, we nevertheless catalog the various defaults of France, Portugal, Prussia, Spain, and the early Italian city-states.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] For private households, it's important to assess the underlying problems and to minimize the risk of financial distress to recur.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In most EU member states, debt discharge is conditioned by a partial payment obligation and by a number of requirements concerning the debtor's behavior.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In the United States (US), discharge is conditioned to a lesser extent.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The spectrum is broad in the EU, with the UK coming closest to the US system (Reifner et al., 2003; Gerhardt, 2009; Frade, 2010).
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The other member states do not provide the option of a debt discharge.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In the US, it is very difficult to discharge federal or federally guaranteed student loan debt by filing bankruptcy.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Even if a debtor proves all three elements, a court may permit only a partial discharge of the student loan.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Student loan borrowers may benefit from restructuring their payments through a Chapter 13 bankruptcy repayment plan, but few qualify for discharge of part or all of their student loan debt.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Bankruptcy fraud is a white-collar crime most typically involving concealment of assets by a debtor to avoid liquidation in bankruptcy proceedings.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] It may include filing of false information, multiple filings in different jurisdictions, bribery, and other acts.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Falsifications on bankruptcy forms often constitute perjury.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Multiple filings are not in and of themselves criminal, but they may violate provisions of bankruptcy law.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In the U.S., bankruptcy fraud statutes are particularly focused on the mental state of particular actions.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Bankruptcy fraud is a federal crime in the United States.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Bankruptcy fraud should be distinguished from *strategic bankruptcy*, which is not a criminal act since it creates a real (not a fake) bankruptcy state.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] However, it may still work against the filer.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] All assets must be disclosed in bankruptcy schedules whether or not the debtor believes the asset has a net value.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] This is because once a bankruptcy petition is filed, it is for the creditors, not the debtor, to decide whether a particular asset has value.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The future ramifications of omitting assets from schedules can be quite serious for the offending debtor.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In the United States, a closed bankruptcy may be reopened by motion of a creditor or the U.S. trustee if a debtor attempts to later assert ownership of such an "unscheduled asset" after being discharged of all debt in the bankruptcy.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The trustee may then seize the asset and liquidate it to benefit the (formerly discharged) creditors.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Whether or not a concealment of such an asset should also be considered for prosecution as fraud or perjury would then be at the discretion of the judge or U.S.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In some countries, such as the United Kingdom, bankruptcy is limited to individuals; other forms of insolvency proceedings (such as liquidation and administration) are applied to companies.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In the United States, *bankruptcy* is applied more broadly to formal insolvency proceedings.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In Argentina, the national Act "24.522 de Concursos y Quiebras" regulates Bankruptcy and Reorganization of individuals and companies; public entities are not included.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] A person may be declared bankrupt with an application submitted to the court by the creditor or with an application to recognize his own bankruptcy.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Legal and natural persons, including individual entrepreneurs, who have an indisputable payment obligation exceeding 60 days and amounting to more than one million AMD can be declared bankrupt.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] All creditors, including the state and municipalities, to whom the person has an obligation that meets the above-mentioned minimum criteria can submit an application to declare a person bankrupt by compulsory procedure.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Basically, these obligations are derived from the legal acts of the court, transactions, the obligation of the debtor to pay taxes, duties, and other fees defined by law.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] At the same time, when being declared bankrupt with a voluntary bankruptcy application, the applicant bears the obligation to prove the fact that the value of his assets is less than his assets by one million AMD or more.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In Australia, bankruptcy is a status which applies to individuals and is governed by the federal *Bankruptcy Act 1966*.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Companies do not go bankrupt but rather go into liquidation or administration, which is governed by the federal *Corporations Act 2001*.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] If a person commits an act of bankruptcy, then a creditor can apply to the Federal Circuit Court or the Federal Court for a sequestration order.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Acts of bankruptcy are defined in the legislation, and include the failure to comply with a bankruptcy notice.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] A bankruptcy notice can be issued where, among other cases, a person fails to pay a judgment debt of at least $5,000.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] A person can also seek to have themselves declared bankrupt for any amount of debt by lodging a debtor's petition with the "Official Receiver", which is the Australian Financial Security Authority (AFSA).
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] All bankrupts must lodge a Statement of Affairs document, also known as a Bankruptcy Form, with AFSA, which includes important information about their assets and liabilities.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] A bankruptcy cannot be discharged until this document has been lodged.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Ordinarily, a bankruptcy lasts three years from the filing of the Statement of Affairs with AFSA.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] A Bankruptcy Trustee (in most cases, the Official Trustee at AFSA) is appointed to deal with all matters regarding the administration of the bankrupt estate.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] For the duration of their bankruptcy, all bankrupts have certain restrictions placed upon them.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] For example, a bankrupt must obtain the permission of their trustee to travel overseas.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Failure to do so may result in the bankrupt being stopped at the airport by the Australian Federal Police.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Additionally, a bankrupt is required to provide their trustee with details of income and assets.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] If the bankrupt does not comply with the Trustee's request to provide details of income, the trustee may have grounds to lodge an Objection to Discharge, which has the effect of extending the bankruptcy for a further three or five years depending on the type of Objection.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The realisation of funds usually comes from two main sources: the bankrupt's assets and the bankrupt's wages.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] There are certain assets that are protected, referred to as *protected assets*.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] These include household furniture and appliances, tools of the trade and vehicles up to a certain value.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] If a house, including the main residence, or car is above a certain value, a third party can buy the interest from the estate in order for the bankrupt to utilise the asset.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] If this is not done, the interest vests in the estate and the trustee is able to take possession of the asset and sell it.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The bankrupt must pay income contributions if their income is above a certain threshold.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] If the bankrupt fails to pay, the trustee can ask the Official Receiver to issue a notice to garnishee the bankrupt's wages.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] If that is not possible, the Trustee may seek to extend the bankruptcy for a further three or five years.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Bankruptcies can be annulled, and the bankrupt released from bankruptcy, prior to the expiration of the normal three-year period if all debts are paid out in full.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Sometimes a bankrupt may be able to raise enough funds to make an Offer of Composition to creditors, which would have the effect of paying the creditors some of the money they are owed.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] If the creditors accept the offer, the bankruptcy can be annulled after the funds are received.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] After the bankruptcy is annulled or the bankrupt has been automatically discharged, the bankrupt's credit report status is shown as "discharged bankrupt" for some years.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The maximum number of years this information can be held is subject to the retention limits under the Privacy Act.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] How long such information is on a credit report may be shorter, depending on the issuing company, but the report must cease to record that information based on the criteria in the Privacy Act.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] It does not apply to state-run companies.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Current law covers three legal proceedings.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The first one is bankruptcy itself ("Falência").
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Bankruptcy is a court-ordered liquidation procedure for an insolvent business.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The final goal of bankruptcy is to liquidate company assets and pay its creditors.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The second one is Court-ordered Restructuring (*Recuperação Judicial*).
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The goal is to overcome the business crisis situation of the debtor in order to allow the continuation of the producer, the employment of workers and the interests of creditors, leading, thus, to preserving company, its corporate function and develop economic activity.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] It is a court procedure required by the debtor which has been in business for more than two years and requires approval by a judge.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The Extrajudicial Restructuring (*Recuperação Extrajudicial*) is a private negotiation that involves creditors and debtors and, as with court-ordered restructuring, also must be approved by courts.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Bankruptcy, also referred to as insolvency in Canada, is governed by the Bankruptcy and Insolvency Act and is applicable to businesses and individuals.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] For example, Target Canada, the Canadian subsidiary of the Target Corporation, the second-largest discount retailer in the United States filed for bankruptcy on 15 January 2015, and closed all of its stores by 12 April.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The office of the Superintendent of Bankruptcy, a federal agency, is responsible for ensuring that bankruptcies are administered in a fair and orderly manner by all licensed Trustees in Canada.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Trustees in bankruptcy, 1041 individuals licensed to administer insolvencies, bankruptcy and proposal estates are governed by the Bankruptcy and Insolvency Act of Canada.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Bankruptcy is filed when a person or a company becomes insolvent and cannot pay their debts as they become due and if they have at least $1,000 in debt.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In 2011, the Superintendent of Bankruptcy reported that trustees in Canada filed 127,774 insolvent estates.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Consumer estates were the vast majority, with 122,999 estates.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The consumer portion of the 2011 volume is divided into 77,993 bankruptcies and 45,006 consumer proposals.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] This represented a reduction of 8.9% from 2010.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Commercial estates filed by Canadian trustees in 2011 4,775 estates, 3,643 bankruptcies and 1,132 Division 1 proposals.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] This represents a reduction of 8.6% over 2010.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Creditors become involved by attending creditors' meetings.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In Canada, a person can file a consumer proposal as an alternative to bankruptcy.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] A consumer proposal is a negotiated settlement between a debtor and their creditors.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] A typical proposal would involve a debtor making monthly payments for a maximum of five years, with the funds distributed to their creditors.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Even though most proposals call for payments of less than the full amount of the debt owing, in most cases, the creditors accept the deal—because if they do not, the next alternative may be personal bankruptcy, in which the creditors get even less money.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The creditors have 45 days to accept or reject the consumer proposal.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Once the proposal is accepted by both the creditors and the Court, the debtor makes the payments to the Proposal Administrator each month (or as otherwise stipulated in their proposal), and the general creditors are prevented from taking any further legal or collection action.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] If the proposal is rejected, the debtor is returned to his prior insolvent state and may have no alternative but to declare personal bankruptcy.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] A consumer proposal can only be made by a debtor with debts to a maximum of $250,000 (not including the mortgage on their principal residence).
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] If debts are greater than $250,000, the proposal must be filed under Division 1 of Part III of the Bankruptcy and Insolvency Act.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] An Administrator is required in the Consumer Proposal, and a Trustee in the Division I Proposal (these are virtually the same although the terms are not interchangeable).
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] A Proposal Administrator is almost always a licensed trustee in bankruptcy, although the Superintendent of Bankruptcy may appoint other people to serve as administrators.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In 2006, there were 98,450 personal insolvency filings in Canada: 79,218 bankruptcies and 19,232 consumer proposals.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In Canada, bankruptcy always means liquidation.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] There is no way for a company to emerge from bankruptcy after restructuring, as is the case in the United States with a Chapter 11 bankruptcy filing.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Canada does, however, have laws that allow for businesses to restructure and emerge later with a smaller debt load and a more positive financial future.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] While not technically a form of bankruptcy, businesses with $5M or more in debt may make use of the Companies' Creditors Arrangement Act to halt all debt recovery efforts against the company while they formulate a plan to restructure.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The People's Republic of China legalized bankruptcy in 1986, and a revised law that was more expansive and complete was enacted in 2007.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Bankruptcy in Ireland applies only to natural persons.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Other insolvency processes including liquidation and examinership are used to deal with corporate insolvency.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Irish bankruptcy law has been the subject of significant comment, from both government sources and the media, as being in need of reform.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Part 7 of the Civil Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2011 has started this process and the government has committed to further reform.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Bankruptcy in Israel is governed by the Insolvency and Rehabilitation Law, 2018.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Insolvency proceedings below ₪150,000 will be administered entirely by the Enforcement and Collection Authority.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Insolvency proceedings above ₪150,000 individual debtors file the documents will be conducted before the official receiver (the Insolvency Commissioner) and, if a creditor want to file against a debtor, he needs to open process, before the magistrate's court that hears in the district.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Company bankruptcy will be conducted before District Court.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] At the end of this audit a payment plan is established, at the end of which the debtor will receive a discharge.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The default scenario is a payment period of three years; however, the court reserves the right to increase or decrease the period depending upon the circumstances of the case.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] If the debtor has no proven financial ability to pay the creditors, he may be granted an immediate discharge.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Since 1996, Israeli personal bankruptcy law has shifted to a relatively debtor-friendly regime, not unlike the American model.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In May 2016, the Parliament of India passed the Insolvency and Bankruptcy Code (IBC), updating outdated corporate insolvency laws.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The IBC streamlined the process, reducing delays from a decade to 180 days, and replaced the Board for Industrial and Financial Reconstruction (BIFR) with a market-driven approach.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Dutch bankruptcy law is governed by the Dutch Bankruptcy Code (*Faillissementswet*).
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Its goal is to reach an agreement with the creditors of the company.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] It is comparable to filing for protection against creditors.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] This proceeding is designed for individuals only and is the result of a court ruling.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The monitor is an independent third party who monitors the individual's ongoing business and decides about financial matters during the period of the *schuldsanering*.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The individual can travel out of the country freely after the judge's decision on the case.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] 127-FZ "On Insolvency (Bankruptcy)" dated 26 October 2002 (as amended) (the "Bankruptcy Act"), replacing the previous law in 1998, to better address the above problems and a broader failure of the action.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Russian insolvency law is intended for a wide range of borrowers: individuals and companies of all sizes, with the exception of state-owned enterprises, government agencies, political parties and religious organizations.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] There are also special rules for insurance companies, professional participants of the securities market, agricultural organizations and other special laws for financial institutions and companies in the natural monopolies in the energy industry.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] 40-FZ "On Insolvency (Bankruptcy)" dated 25 February 1999 (as amended) (the "Insolvency Law of Credit Institutions") contains special provisions in relation to the opening of insolvency proceedings in relation to the credit company.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Insolvency Provisions Act, credit organizations used in conjunction with the provisions of the Bankruptcy Act.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The main face of the bankruptcy process is the insolvency officer (trustee in bankruptcy, bankruptcy manager).
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] At various stages of bankruptcy, he must be determined: the temporary officer in monitoring procedure, external manager in external control, the receiver or administrative officer in the economic recovery, the liquidator.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] During the bankruptcy trustee in bankruptcy (insolvency officer) has a decisive influence on the movement of assets (property) of the debtor – the debtor and has a key influence on the economic and legal aspects of its operations.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In Spain, people who cannot repay their home mortgages may declare bankruptcy.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Bankruptcy and foreclosure discharges the obligation to pay mortgage interest, but not mortgage principal.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] If mortgage principal is not paid, the debtor is placed on a list of untrustworthy people.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Under Swiss law, bankruptcy can be a consequence of insolvency.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] It is a court-ordered form of debt enforcement proceedings that applies, in general, to registered commercial entities only.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In a bankruptcy, all assets of the debtor are liquidated under the administration of the creditors, although the law provides for debt restructuring options similar to those under Chapter 11 of the U.S.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In Sweden, bankruptcy (Swedish: *konkurs*) is a formal process that may involve a company or individual.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] A creditor or the company itself can apply for bankruptcy.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] An external bankruptcy manager takes over the company or the assets of the person, and tries to sell as much as possible.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] A person or a company in bankruptcy cannot access its assets (with some exceptions).
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The formal bankruptcy process is rarely carried out for individuals.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Creditors can claim money through the Enforcement Administration anyway, and creditors do not usually benefit from the bankruptcy of individuals because there are costs of a bankruptcy manager which has priority.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Unpaid debts remain after bankruptcy for individuals.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] People who are deeply in debt can obtain a debt arrangement procedure (Swedish: *skuldsanering*).
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] On application, they obtain a payment plan under which they pay as much as they can for five years, and then all remaining debts are cancelled.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Debts that derive from a ban on business operations (issued by court, commonly for tax fraud or fraudulent business practices) or owed to a crime victim as compensation for damages, are exempted from this—and, as before this process was introduced in 2006, remain lifelong.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Debts that have not been claimed during a 3–10 year period are cancelled.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Often crime victims stop their claims after a few years since criminals often do not have job incomes and might be hard to locate, while banks make sure their claims are not cancelled.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The most common reasons for personal insolvency in Sweden are illness, unemployment, divorce or company bankruptcy.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] For companies, formal bankruptcy is a normal effect of insolvency, even if there is a reconstruction mechanism where the company can be given time to solve its situation, e.g. by finding an investor.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The government can pay salaries to employees in insolvent companies which do not pay them, but only if the company is declared bankrupt.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Therefore, it is normal that trade union do the application for bankruptcy if a supplier has not already done so.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The formal bankruptcy involves contracting a bankruptcy manager, who makes certain that assets are sold and money divided by the priority the law claims, and no other way.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] After a finished bankruptcy for a company, it is terminated.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The activities might continue in a new company which has bought important assets from the bankrupted company.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The United Arab Emirates Bankruptcy Law came into force on 29 December 2016, and created a single law governing bankruptcy procedures, which had previously been spread across multiple sources.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] There are two court procedures: first, a procedure for a company that is not yet insolvent, known as a protective composition, and second, a formal bankruptcy that is split into a rescue process (similar to protective composition) or liquidation.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Directors of a company can be held personally liable for its debts.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The Bankruptcy Law does not apply to government bodies, or to companies trading in free zones such as the Dubai International Financial Centre or the Abu Dhabi Global Market, which have their own insolvency laws.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Bankruptcy in the United Kingdom (in a strict legal sense) relates only to individuals (including sole proprietors) and partnerships.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Companies and other corporations enter into differently named legal insolvency procedures: liquidation and administration (administration order and administrative receivership).
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] However, the term 'bankruptcy' is often used when referring to companies in the media and in general conversation.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Bankruptcy in Scotland is referred to as sequestration.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] To apply for bankruptcy in Scotland, an individual must have more than £1,500 of debt.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] A trustee in bankruptcy must be either an Official Receiver (a civil servant) or a licensed insolvency practitioner.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Current law in England and Wales derives in large part from the Insolvency Act 1986.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Following the introduction of the Enterprise Act 2002, bankruptcy in England and Wales now normally lasts no longer than 12 months, and may be less if the Official Receiver files in court a certificate that investigations are complete.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] It was expected that the UK Government's liberalisation of the bankruptcy regime would increase the number of bankruptcy cases; initially, cases increased, as the Insolvency Service statistics appear to bear out.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Since 2009, the introduction of the Debt Relief Order has resulted in a dramatic fall in bankruptcies, the latest estimates for year 2014/15 being significantly less than 30,000 cases.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The UK bankruptcy law was changed in May 2000, effective from 29 May 2000.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Debtors may now retain occupational pensions while in bankruptcy, except in rare cases.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In the United Kingdom, creditors can have a court declare a person who owes them money declared bankrupt involuntarily.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] This can be done when a creditor can prove that they are owed a debt of £5,000 or a share of a person's debts totaling at least £5,000.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Bankruptcy in the United States is a matter placed under federal jurisdiction by the United States Constitution (in Article 1, Section 8, Clause 4), which empowers Congress to enact "uniform Laws on the subject of Bankruptcies throughout the United States".
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Congress has enacted statutes governing bankruptcy, primarily in the form of the Bankruptcy Code, located at Title 11 of the United States Code.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] A debtor declares bankruptcy to obtain relief from debt, and this is normally accomplished either through a discharge of the debt or through a restructuring of the debt.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] When a debtor files a voluntary petition, their bankruptcy case commences.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] While bankruptcy cases are always filed in United States Bankruptcy Court (an adjunct to the U.S.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] District Courts), bankruptcy cases, particularly with respect to the validity of claims and exemptions, are often dependent upon State law.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] A Bankruptcy Exemption defines the property a debtor may retain and preserve through bankruptcy.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Certain real and personal property can be exempted on "Schedule C" of a debtor's bankruptcy forms, and effectively be taken outside the debtor's bankruptcy estate.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Bankruptcy exemptions are available only to individuals filing bankruptcy.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] There are two alternative systems that can be used to exempt property from a bankruptcy estate, federal exemptions (available in some states but not all), and state exemptions (which vary widely between states).
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] For example, Maryland and Virginia, which are adjoining states, have different personal exemption amounts that cannot be seized for payment of debts.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] This amount is the first $6,000 in property or cash in Maryland, but normally only the first $5,000 in Virginia.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] State law therefore plays a major role in many bankruptcy cases, such that there may be significant differences in the outcome of a bankruptcy case depending upon the state in which it is filed.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] An important feature applicable to all types of bankruptcy filings is the automatic stay.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The automatic stay means that the mere request for bankruptcy protection automatically halts most lawsuits, repossessions, foreclosures, evictions, garnishments, attachments, utility shut-offs, and debt collection activity.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The most common types of personal bankruptcy for individuals are Chapter 7 and Chapter 13.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Chapter 7, known as a "straight bankruptcy", involves the discharge of certain debts without repayment.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Chapter 13 involves a plan of repayment of debts over a period of years.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Whether a person qualifies for Chapter 7 or Chapter 13 is in part determined by income.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] As many as 65% of all US consumer bankruptcy filings are Chapter 7 cases.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Some studies of the operation of the credit counseling requirement suggest that it provides little benefit to debtors who receive the counseling because the only realistic option for many is to seek relief under the Bankruptcy Code.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Corporations and other business forms normally file under Chapters 7 or 11.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Often called "straight bankruptcy" or "simple bankruptcy", a Chapter 7 bankruptcy potentially allows debtors to eliminate most or all of their debts over a period of as little as three or four months.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In a typical consumer bankruptcy, the only debts that survive a Chapter 7 are student loans, child support obligations, some tax bills, and criminal fines.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Credit cards, pay day loans, personal loans, medical bills, and just about all other bills are discharged.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In Chapter 7, a debtor surrenders non-exempt property to a bankruptcy trustee, who then liquidates the property and distributes the proceeds to the debtor's unsecured creditors.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In exchange, the debtor is entitled to a discharge of some debt.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] However, the debtor is not granted a discharge if guilty of certain types of inappropriate behavior (e.g., concealing records relating to financial condition) and certain debts (e.g., spousal and child support and most student loans).
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Some taxes are not discharged even though the debtor is generally discharged from debt.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Many individuals in financial distress own only exempt property (e.g., clothes, household goods, an older car, or the tools of their trade or profession) and do not have to surrender any property to the trustee.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The amount of property that a debtor may exempt varies from state to state (as noted above, Virginia and Maryland have a $1,000 difference).
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Chapter 7 relief is available only once in any eight-year period.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Generally, the rights of secured creditors to their collateral continues, even though their debt is discharged.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] For example, absent some arrangement by a debtor to surrender a car or "reaffirm" a debt, the creditor with a security interest in the debtor's car may repossess the car even if the debt to the creditor is discharged.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Ninety-one percent of US individuals who petition for relief under Chapter 7 hire an attorney to file their petitions.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The typical cost of an attorney is $1,170.00.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Alternatives to filing with an attorney are: filing pro se, hiring a non-lawyer petition preparer, or using online software to generate the petition.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] To be eligible to file a consumer bankruptcy under Chapter 7, a debtor must qualify under a statutory means test.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The means test was intended to make it more difficult for a significant number of financially distressed individual debtors whose debts are primarily consumer debts to qualify for relief under Chapter 7 of the Bankruptcy Code.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The "means test" is employed in cases where an individual with primarily consumer debts has more than the average annual income for a household of equivalent size, computed over a 180-day period prior to filing.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] If the individual must take the means test, their average monthly income over this 180-day period is reduced by a series of allowances for living expenses and secured debt payments in a very complex calculation that may or may not accurately reflect that individual's actual monthly budget.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] If the results of the means test show no disposable income (or in some cases a very small amount) then the individual qualifies for Chapter 7 relief.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] An individual who fails the means test will have their Chapter 7 case dismissed, or may have to convert the case to a Chapter 13 bankruptcy.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Generally, a trustee sells most of the debtor's assets to pay off creditors.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] However, certain debtor assets will be protected to some extent by bankruptcy exemptions.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] These include Social Security payments, unemployment compensation, limited equity in a home, car, or truck, household goods and appliances, trade tools, and books.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] However, these exemptions vary from state to state.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In Chapter 11 bankruptcy, the debtor retains ownership and control of assets and is re-termed a debtor in possession (DIP).
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The debtor in possession runs the day-to-day operations of the business while creditors and the debtor work with the Bankruptcy Court in order to negotiate and complete a plan.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Upon meeting certain requirements (e.g., fairness among creditors, priority of certain creditors) creditors are permitted to vote on the proposed plan.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] If a plan is confirmed, the debtor continues to operate and pay debts under the terms of the confirmed plan.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] If a specified majority of creditors do not vote to confirm a plan, additional requirements may be imposed by the court in order to confirm the plan.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Debtors filing for Chapter 11 protection a second time are known informally as "Chapter 22" filers.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In a corporate or business bankruptcy, an indebted company is typically recapitalized so that it emerges from bankruptcy with more equity and less debt, with potential for dispute over the valuation of the reorganized business.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In Chapter 13, debtors retain ownership and possession of all their assets but must devote some portion of future income to repaying creditors, generally over three to five years.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The amount of payment and period of the repayment plan depend upon a variety of factors, including the value of the debtor's property and the amount of a debtor's income and expenses.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Under this chapter, the debtor can propose a repayment plan in which to pay creditors over three to five years.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] If the monthly income is less than the state's median income, the plan is for three years, unless the court finds just cause to extend the plan for a longer period.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] If the debtor's monthly income is greater than the median income for individuals in the debtor's state, the plan must generally be for five years.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] A plan cannot exceed the five-year limit.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Relief under Chapter 13 is available only to individuals with regular income whose debts do not exceed prescribed limits.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] If the debtor is an individual or a sole proprietor, the debtor is allowed to file for a Chapter 13 bankruptcy to repay all or part of the debts.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Secured creditors may be entitled to greater payment than unsecured creditors.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In contrast to Chapter 7, the debtor in Chapter 13 may keep all property, whether or not exempt.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] If the plan appears feasible and if the debtor complies with all the other requirements, the bankruptcy court typically confirms the plan and the debtor and creditors are bound by its terms.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Creditors have no say in the formulation of the plan, other than to object to it, if appropriate, on the grounds that it does not comply with one of the Code's statutory requirements.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Generally, the debtor makes payments to a trustee who disburses the funds in accordance with the terms of the confirmed plan.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] When the debtor completes payments pursuant to the terms of the plan, the court formally grant the debtor a discharge of the debts provided for in the plan.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] However, if the debtor fails to make the agreed upon payments or fails to seek or gain court approval of a modified plan, a bankruptcy court will normally dismiss the case on the motion of the trustee.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] After a dismissal, creditors may resume pursuit of state law remedies to recover the unpaid debt.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In 2004, the number of insolvencies reached record highs in many European countries.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In France, company insolvencies rose by more than 4%, in Austria by more than 10%, and in Greece by more than 20%.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The increase in the number of insolvencies, however, does not indicate the total financial impact of insolvencies in each country because there is no indication of the size of each case.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] An increase in the number of bankruptcy cases does not necessarily entail an increase in bad debt write-off rates for the economy as a whole.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Bankruptcy statistics are also a trailing indicator.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] There is a time delay between financial difficulties and bankruptcy.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] In most cases, several months or even years pass between the financial problems and the start of bankruptcy proceedings.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Legal, tax, and cultural issues may further distort bankruptcy figures, especially when comparing on an international basis.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] The insolvency numbers for private individuals also do not show the whole picture.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Only a fraction of heavily indebted households file for insolvency.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Two of the main reasons for this are the stigma of declaring themselves insolvent and the potential business disadvantage.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Following the soar in insolvencies in the previous decade, a number of European countries, such as France, Germany, Spain and Italy, began to revamp their bankruptcy laws in 2013.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] They modelled these new laws on Chapter 11 of the U.S.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Currently, the majority of insolvency cases have ended in liquidation in Europe rather than the businesses surviving the crisis.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] These new law models are meant to change this; lawmakers are hoping to turn bankruptcy into a chance for restructuring rather than a death sentence for the companies.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] EU policy aims to ensure that "honest entrepreneurs" are afforded a second chance at business development.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] A faster start-up programme for people affected by bankruptcy operating in Denmark and a scheme to support Belgian business owners and self-employed persons were highlighted in a 2008 European Commission *Communication* as good practice examples in this field.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] Technically, states do not collapse directly due to a sovereign default event itself.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] However, the tumultuous events that follow may bring down the state, so in common language, states would be described as being bankrupted.
[src:aaron-manby/bankruptcy] An example of this is when the Goguryeo–Sui War in 614 A.D. ended in the disintegration of Sui dynasty China within 4 years, although their enemy Goguryeo (occupying modern Korea) also seemingly entered into decline and fell some 56 years later.
[src:aaron-manby/bowsprit] The **bowsprit** of a sailing vessel is a spar extending forward from the vessel's prow.
[src:aaron-manby/bowsprit] The bowsprit is typically held down by a bobstay that counteracts the forces from the forestays.
[src:aaron-manby/bowsprit] The bowsprit’s purpose is to create anchor points for the sails that extend beyond the vessel’s bow, increasing the size of sail that may be held taut.
[src:aaron-manby/bowsprit] The word *bowsprit* is thought to originate from the Middle Low German word *bōchsprēt* – *bōch* meaning "bow" and *sprēt* meaning "pole".
[src:aaron-manby/bowsprit] On some square-rigged ships a spritsail is flown below the bowsprit; these are sometimes accompanied by a sprit topmast, which serves to assist the spritsail while tacking.
[src:aaron-manby/bowsprit] The bowsprit may also be used to hold up the figurehead.
[src:aaron-manby/builder-s-old-measurement] The Builder's Old Measurement formula remained in effect until the advent of steam propulsion.
[src:aaron-manby/builder-s-old-measurement] Steamships required a different method of estimating tonnage, because the ratio of length to beam was larger and a significant volume of internal space was used for boilers and machinery.
[src:aaron-manby/builder-s-old-measurement] In 1849, the Moorsom System was created in the United Kingdom.
[src:aaron-manby/builder-s-old-measurement] The Moorsom system calculates the cargo-carrying capacity in cubic feet, another method of volumetric measurement.
[src:aaron-manby/builder-s-old-measurement] The capacity in cubic feet is then divided by 100 cubic feet (2.8 m3) of capacity per gross ton, resulting in a tonnage expressed in tons.
[src:aaron-manby/builder-s-old-measurement] King Edward I levied the first tax on the hire of ships in England in 1303 based on tons burthen.
[src:aaron-manby/builder-s-old-measurement] Later, King Edward III levied a tax of 3 shillings on each tun of imported wine, roughly equivalent to £149 in 2025.
[src:aaron-manby/builder-s-old-measurement] At that time a tun was a wine container of 252 wine gallons, approx 210 imp gal (955 L) weighing about 2,240 lb (1,020 kg), a weight known today as a long ton or imperial ton.
[src:aaron-manby/builder-s-old-measurement] The numerator yields the ship's volume expressed in cubic feet.
[src:aaron-manby/builder-s-old-measurement] If a tun is deemed to be equivalent to 100 cubic feet, then the tonnage is simply the number of such 100 cubic feet 'tun' units of volume.
[src:aaron-manby/builder-s-old-measurement] In 1678 Thames shipbuilders used a method assuming that a ship's burden would be 3⁄5 of its displacement.
[src:aaron-manby/builder-s-old-measurement] This formula remained in effect until the Builder's Old Measurement rule (above) was put into use in 1720, and then mandated by Act of Parliament in 1773.
[src:aaron-manby/builder-s-old-measurement] itself, at the ship's midpoint, to the top of the uppermost full length deck.
[src:aaron-manby/builder-s-old-measurement] Interior space; The height from the lowest part of the hull inside the ship, at its midpoint, to the ceiling that is made up of the uppermost full length deck.
[src:aaron-manby/builder-s-old-measurement] , that is used in context of depth measurement, is usually defined as the uppermost full length deck.
[src:aaron-manby/builder-s-old-measurement] The British took the length measurement from the outside of the stem to the outside of the sternpost, whereas the Americans measured from inside the posts.
[src:aaron-manby/builder-s-old-measurement] The British measured breadth from outside the planks, whereas the Americans measured the breadth from inside the planks.
[src:aaron-manby/builder-s-old-measurement] Lastly, the British divided by 94, whereas the Americans divided by 95.
[src:aaron-manby/builder-s-old-measurement] The upshot was that American calculations gave a lower number than the British ones.
[src:aaron-manby/builder-s-old-measurement] The British measure yields values about 6% greater than the American.
[src:aaron-manby/builder-s-old-measurement] For instance, when the British measured the captured USS *President*, their calculations gave her a burthen of 1533+7⁄94 tons, whereas the American calculations gave the burthen as 1444 tons.
[src:aaron-manby/builder-s-old-measurement] The US system was in use from 1789 until 1864, when a modified version of the Moorsom System was adopted.
[src:aaron-manby/builder-s-old-measurement] A similar method was used in France to assess the cargo capacity of ships.
[src:aaron-manby/builder-s-old-measurement] This was standardised in 1681 at 1 tonne burthen per 42 French cubic feet.
[src:aaron-manby/builder-s-old-measurement] Prior to metrification this unit was called a *port* (from *porter*, transl. to carry) *tonneau* (plural *tonneaux*).
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] Manby was born in Cowes on the Isle of Wight to Aaron and Juliana Manby, née Fewster.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] Aaron Manby was a successful engineer building bridges, ships and engines.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] As a child Charles attended a Roman Catholic seminary; in 1814 he attended well disciplined Saint-Servan College near Rennes, but returned to England in 1815 having turned down the opportunity of joining the military under a commission organised by his uncle.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] Manby's father was the founder, and from 1812, the managing partner of the Horseley Ironworks at Tipton, Staffordshire.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] In 1817, Charles began training as an engineer at the Ironworks working for such notable engineers as John Rennie and Thomas Telford.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] During his training he helped with projects at West India Docks and the iron paddleship which was named *Aaron Manby*.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] This was made in parts at the Ironworks and then transported to the Surrey Canal Dock on the River Thames in London.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] The ship was then reassembled with Charles Manby supervising the installation of the vessel's steam engine.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] Despite being only 18 years old, Manby was designated as the chief engineer during its maiden voyage on 10 June 1822 with Sir Charles Napier as captain.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] During this voyage across the English Channel, the vessel became the first iron ship to carry cargo from London to Paris.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] In 1823 Manby started work installing hydrogen gas pipes in Paris, employed by the French company *Compagnie d'Carriage par de gaz Hydrogen*; The company had been founded by Daniel Wilson and Manby's father the year before.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] Still employed in France by his father, Manby worked at a gas works at Ternes, then later reorganised the ironworks at Le Creusot.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] Manby's fluency in the French language was an asset throughout his life.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] Manby was then employed by the French government creating France's state-owned tobacco factories.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] Charles then returned to the UK and took over the management of the Beaufort Iron Works in Beaufort, Blaenau Gwent where he married Ellen Jones in 1830.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] He briefly managed the Bristol Iron Works, but in 1834 he moved to London and began practising there as a civil engineer.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] He and Henry Cruger Price marketed the 'Price and Manby System' a new type of ventilation system for whole buildings.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] The business lasted until 1843 when their offices in Bristol and London closed.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] Manby had become involved with the Arctic explorer Sir John Ross's India Steamship Company which he joined in 1838.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] The company's objective was to establish a steamship service to India, but it was quickly taken over by the Peninsular and Oriental Steam Navigation Company.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] Charles Manby then became Secretary of the Institution of Civil Engineers (ICE) in November 1839, succeeding Thomas Webster.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] He nominally retired from this role in 1856 and was awarded a testimonial, a prize and a purse of 2,000 pounds from the chairman Robert Stephenson.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] The next secretary was Manby's former assistant James Forrest.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] Manby remained involved in the organisation and participated in its activities as Honorary Secretary until his death.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] Manby helped Samuel Colt's company to create a factory in Pimlico to manufacture firearms.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] Colt had received a lot of interest in his revolvers at the Great Exhibition in 1851 and Manby had been involved in the organisation of the exhibition arranging financial underwriting for Sir Robert Peel.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] Manby negotiated a lease with the British Government which enabled Colt to go into full production three years later.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] Colt was able to make a profit during the Crimean War, but the factory closed in 1856 shortly after the end of the war.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] In 1853 Manby became a Fellow of the Royal Society and in 1856 he became the London representative of locomotive manufacturer Robert Stephenson and Company.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] Manby moved next door to Stephenson and travelled across Europe to represent the locomotive company using the contacts which he had created during his 17 years as secretary of the ICE.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] Charles Manby was chosen with James Rendel and John Robinson McClean to join the International Scientific Commission on the Suez Canal.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] This was based in Paris where his French language was again useful.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] His knowledge of engineering and his linguistic skills helped him serve as one of the secretaries to the International Commission for the piercing of the isthmus of Suez, with Jules Barthélemy-Saint-Hilaire and Lieutenant Lieussou.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] In 1858, Manby, by now a childless widower, married Harriet Willard, the widow of publisher W.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] He died on 31 July 1884, at Ranelagh House, 10 Lower Grosvenor Place, London.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] In 1860, Manby helped create the Engineer & Railway Volunteer Staff Corps (today, the British Army Reserve's Engineer and Logistic Staff Corps.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] As a result, Manby became a lieutenant-colonel.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] Manby left an estate of just under £250.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-manby] Today his home at 60 Westbourne Terrace in London is identified by a blue plaque.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Admiral **Sir Charles John Napier** KCB (6 March 1786 – 6 November 1860) was a British naval officer and politician who served for sixty years in the Royal Navy, seeing action in the French Revolutionary and Napoleonic Wars, War of 1812, Syrian War and Crimean War.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] For a period he also commanded the Portuguese Navy during the Liberal Wars.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] An innovator concerned with the development of ironclads, and an advocate of human reforms in the Royal Navy, Napier was also active in politics as a Liberal Member of Parliament and was probably the naval officer most widely known to the public in the early Victorian era.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Napier became a midshipman in 1799 aboard the 16-gun sloop HMS *Martin*, but left her in May 1800 before she was lost with all hands.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He next served aboard *Renown*, flagship of Sir John Borlase Warren.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] After this, in November 1802, he transferred to the frigate *Greyhound* under Captain William Hoste.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] The following year, he moved to *Égyptienne* for a voyage to St Helena escorting a convoy of ships and then in the English Channel and off the coast of France.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] (In later years, feeling he had been badly treated as a midshipman by her captain, Charles Fleeming, Napier challenged that officer to a duel, though they were eventually reconciled by their seconds.) In 1804–5 he served briefly on *Mediator* before moving to HMS *Renommée* off Boulogne.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He was promoted lieutenant on 30 November 1805.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He was appointed to *Courageux*, and was present in her in the West Indies at the action in which the squadron under Admiral Warren took the French *Marengo* (80 guns) and *Belle Poule* (40 guns), on 13 March 1806.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] After returning home with Warren, he returned to the West Indies in HMS *St George* and having been promoted to commander on 30 November 1807, he was appointed acting commander of the brig *Pultusk* of 16 guns, formerly the French privateer *Austerlitz*.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] In August 1808 he became captain of the brig-sloop HMS *Recruit* (18 guns), and in her fought a hot action off Antigua with the French sloop *Diligente* (18 guns), in which his thigh was smashed by a cannonball.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] In April 1809, Napier took part in the capture of the Caribbean island of Martinique, and subsequently distinguished himself in the pursuit of three escaping French ships of the line, handling the small *Recruit* so well that the British were able to capture the French flagship *D'Hautpoul*.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] As a result, he was promoted acting post captain and briefly given the command of the captured 74-gun ship-of-the-line.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] His rank was confirmed on 22 May 1809, but he was put on half-pay, when he came home as temporary captain of the frigate *Jason* escorting a convoy.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] While on half-pay he spent some time at the University of Edinburgh.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Napier, still on half-pay, then went to Portugal to visit his three cousins, (all colonels serving in Wellington's army, and one of whom was Charles James Napier, the future conqueror of Sindh).
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He took part in the Battle of Buçaco, during which he saved his cousin Charles's life and was himself wounded.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] In 1811, he was appointed captain of the frigate HMS *Thames* (32 guns) and served in the Mediterranean Fleet under Sir Edward Pellew, disrupting enemy shipping.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Among his principal exploits was the 1813 capture of the island of Ponza, which was a possible haven for corsairs.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] In 1813 he moved to command the frigate *Euryalus* (36 guns), operating mainly off the French and Spanish Mediterranean coast.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] After the surrender of Napoleon and his first period of exile in 1814, Napier and his ship were transferred to the coast of North America, where the War of 1812 with the United States was still in progress, now commanded by Vice Admiral Sir Alexander Cochrane.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] In the Chesapeake Bay campaign, he took part in the August expedition up the Potomac River to Alexandria (southeast of the American national capital), Arriving several days after the Burning of Washington and the Battle of Bladensburg under Maj.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Robert Ross and Rear Admiral Sir George Cockburn, he was second in command to Captain James Alexander Gordon.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] The town of Alexandria capitulated with a ransom paid and the shipping there was seized.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] The squadron successfully withdrew downriver with their prizes despite frequent harassing American attacks from the shores downstream.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] During the withdrawal, Napier was wounded in the neck.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He next distinguished himself in the following attack on Baltimore, Maryland, by a British Army accompanied by 16 warships, 12–14 September 1814, under Admirals Cochrane, and Cockburn.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] HMS *Euryalus* was involved in the bombardment of Fort McHenry, protecting the city on the Northwest Branch of the Patapsco River that began early in the morning of the 13th.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] At. the same time, earlier on the 12th, Gen.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Ross had been put ashore to the southeast at North Point with his regiments to attack the town from the east.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He was shot in a brief skirmish just before his troops met the City Brigade regiments of the Maryland Militia under Brig.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] John Stricker at the Battle of North Point that afternoon.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] After pausing for the night to tend to the substantial wounded and now under the command of Col.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Arthur Brooke, the regiments waited outside the substantial American dug-in fortifications with opposing approx.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] 20,000 troops and 100 artillery at old Loudenschlager's Hill in present-day Hampstead Hill in western Patterson Park until the naval forces were able to subdue the fort and move upriver to attack the eastern land redoubts.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Before they could land, however, they were detected and subjected to a withering fire from the still active guns of Fort McHenry and two smaller forts to the west, batteries Covington and Babcock.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] The British fought back strongly with cannon and rockets, but Napier's force eventually retreated to the warships with substantial casualties, and Cochrane's fleet later withdrew on the morning of the 14th.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] With Napoleon's escape from Elba and brief return to power, the Hundred Days, *Euryalus* returned to Britain.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Napier's last mission of the Napoleonic wars was to land troops at the mouth of the River Scheldt to guard against the French advance into Belgium.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] At the end of the war Napier was made a Companion of the Bath (4 June 1815).
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He married Frances Elizabeth Elers, née Younghusband, generally referred to as Eliza, whom he had known and loved in Edinburgh while still a teenager.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] In the meantime Eliza had married a Lieutenant Edward Elers and been widowed.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] She had four children whom Napier adopted as his own.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Of these the second son, Charles Elers Napier, became a naval officer.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] The eldest, Edward Elers Napier, entered the army, rising to the rank of major-general: he also wrote books of travel and reminiscence, as well as the authoritative biography of his stepfather.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Frances also gave Napier two children of his own, a son born in Rome and a daughter born by Lake Geneva.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] The son, Charles, died as a result of an accident aged five.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] The first years of his leisure Napier spent in Italy, Switzerland (where he briefly took up farming), and in Paris.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He had inherited considerable wealth from his mother's side of the family and spent it freely.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] During these years Napier began a voluminous and indefatigable correspondence with the Admiralty on the urgency for naval reform, which lasted for the rest of his career.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He sought to persuade successive civil administrations of the need for innovative ship-design and tactics, the development of steam ships and the use of iron in ship construction, the proper training of officers, and decent living conditions for ordinary seamen.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He held that the use of the press gang and of flogging should be abolished, and that seamen should receive proper wages and pensions.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] In all this he was far ahead of his time.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] His advocacy had little effect: on the contrary, successive administrators considered him an eccentric nuisance.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He had been interested in steam navigation since its beginnings, and began investing his considerable resources in a steam vessel service that would ply along the River Seine.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] In 1821 he financed and participated in the construction of one of the first iron-hulled vessels ever built, and the first designed to venture into open water.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] The *Aaron Manby* was named after the master of the Horseley Ironworks, Tipton, Staffordshire, where she was pre-fabricated to a design formulated by Napier, Manby and Manby's son Charles and then assembled at Rotherhithe on the Thames.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] After trials in May 1822, the *Aaron Manby* crossed the English Channel to Le Havre under Napier's command on 10 June 1822, and proceeded up the Seine to Paris, where she caused a great stir and where she was based for the next decade.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] This has been claimed as the first passage from France to Britain by steam ship, which it was not: but it was the first direct passage from London to Paris by steam ship and the first seagoing voyage by an iron ship anywhere.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Napier's company built five similar steamships but in 1827 he went bankrupt, leaving the family in severe financial difficulty.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] At the beginning of 1829, he was appointed to command the 42-gun frigate *Galatea*.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] The Admiralty gave him permission to fit her with paddles of his own design, worked by winches on the main deck.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He carried out trials that proved that ships could travel independently of the wind.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] The Admiralty, however, did not adopt this innovation.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] At the start of Portugal's Liberal Wars in 1832 Napier was at the Azores, which were the only part of Portuguese territory still held for Queen Maria II of Portugal against the usurpation of her uncle, the absolutist Dom Miguel.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He so impressed the constitutional leaders, especially the Count de Vila Flor (better known by his later title of Duke of Terceira), that they begged him to take command of their small fleet.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Having unsuccessfully contested the parliamentary by-election for Portsmouth in June 1832 after *Galatea* was paid off, he accepted their proposals in February 1833.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Sailing to Portugal with his stepson Charles Elers Napier as aide-de-camp, bringing troop reinforcements and using the incognito of 'Carlos da Ponza', he arrived in Porto, where Queen Maria's father Dom Pedro, ex-Emperor of Brazil, and the Liberal forces were being besieged by Miguel's armies.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He assumed command of the Liberal fleet, succeeding its previous British commander George Rose Sartorius.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] With the fleet Napier then transported the Liberal army to the Algarve to open a second front in the south of the country.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] On his return voyage he destroyed the much larger Miguelite fleet in the Battle of Cape St Vincent on 5 July 1833.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] These two strokes enabled the Liberals to capture Lisbon, which the Miguelites abandoned, though Napier's squadron was now ravaged by cholera.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] On the demand of France Napier was struck off the British navy list.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] On the other hand, Dom Pedro appointed him Admiral of the Portuguese Navy on 10 July.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Napier's victory, with a fleet largely manned by British seamen, was viewed in Britain as a credit to the Royal Navy.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] The victory and consequent accolades greatly annoyed King William IV, who disliked both Napier and Dom Pedro.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Continuing his Portuguese services, Napier commanded land forces in the successful defence of Lisbon, September 1833.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] For these services he was made Commander of the Tower and Sword, and Count of the Cape of Saint Vincent in the Peerage of Portugal.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] On 12 September 1833, he captured *The Lord of the Isles* steamer at Sao Martinho and in 1836 defended his prize in the Court of Common Pleas.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] In 1834, with a small army made up largely of British sailors, he reconquered the Minho region for the constitutional cause.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] After the final defeat of Miguel and the death of Dom Pedro shortly afterwards, Napier found himself frustrated in his attempts to reform the naval administration of Portugal and returned to England.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] His departure was followed by a vote of thanks to him in both houses of the restored Portuguese parliament.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Napier unsuccessfully contested the Portsmouth parliamentary seat for a second time in the by-election of December 1834.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He then occupied himself until 1836 with writing a history of the Portuguese War and his own part in it.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Though he published his *An Account of the War in Portugal* as 'Admiral Charles Napier', he was only an Admiral as far as Portugal was concerned.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He was restored to his former rank of captain in the British Navy List by an Order in Council on 9 March 1836, and in July 1837 unsuccessfully contested the by-election for Greenwich in the Liberal cause.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] In 1838 received command of the ship of the line HMS *Powerful* (84 guns).
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] When troubles broke out in Syria and Muhammad Ali, ruler of Egypt, invaded it and destroyed a Turkish army, Napier was ordered to the Mediterranean.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] On the evening of 29 May 1839 *Powerful* was anchored in the Cove of Cork, Ireland when urgent orders came from the Admiralty to proceed at once to Malta.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He was also informed that the ships-of-the-line *Ganges* and *Implacable* had already started from England.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Wishing to overtake them, Napier set sail at 2 a.m. on the 30th for Gibraltar.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] In the summer of 1840 the Maronite Christians of Lebanon rose in revolt against the occupying Egyptians and Muhammad Ali in retaliation sent Ibrahim Pasha with 15,000 troops to burn towns and villages along the Lebanese coast.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] By 1 July 1840 Napier, with a detached squadron and the rank of commodore, was patrolling the coast to protect British interests.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Meanwhile, Stopford, claiming his flag of truce had been fired on, bombarded Beirut, killing many civilians.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Napier next distinguished himself by leading an attack by land and sea on Sidon, the Egyptian army's southern base, which capitulated on 28 September.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] The Egyptians abandoned Beirut on 3 October.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] While preparing to attack them at Boharsef, Napier was ordered to relinquish command of the army to withdraw and hand over the land forces to the now recovered Brigadier-General Smith.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] To do so would have meant giving up the tactical initiative, and Napier accordingly disobeyed the order and continued with the attack against Ibrahim's army.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] The ensuing Battle of Boharsef, on 10 October, was a hard-fought victory, one of the very few land battles won by a naval officer.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] By the end of the month the only coastal position still held by the Egyptians was Acre, which Stopford was instructed to recapture.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] On 3 November the Mediterranean Fleet, with its Turkish and Austrian allies, moved into position against the western and southern sides of the town.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] The fire of the ships (48,000 rounds in all) was devastatingly accurate.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] A shell penetrated the main magazine in the south of the city, which exploded killing 1,100 men.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] British losses were only 18 men killed and 41 wounded.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] During the action, Napier had manoeuvred independently against Stopford's orders and his division, by accident and mutual misunderstandings, left a space in the fleet's deployment, not that this affected the outcome.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Some captains wanted Napier to be court-martialled for insubordination, but Stopford did not push the issue.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] The rapid collapse of Muhammad Ali's power, with the prospect of bloody chaos in Egypt, was not part of the Allies' plan, so Stopford sent Napier to command the squadron at Alexandria and to observe the situation.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Here, acting once again on his own initiative, Napier appeared before the city on 25 November and enforced a blockade.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Napier, without reference to his admiral or the British government, personally negotiated a peace with Muhammad Ali.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] The treaty guaranteed Muhammad Ali and his heirs the sovereignty of Egypt, and pledged to evacuate Ibrahim's beleaguered army back to Alexandria, if Muhammad Ali in turn renounced all claims to Syria, submitted to the Sultan and returned the Ottoman fleet.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] 'I do not know if I have done right in settling the eastern question', Napier wrote on 26 November to Lord Minto, the First Lord of the Admiralty.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Stopford repudiated the arrangement immediately when he had heard the news; the Sultan and the British ambassador were furious, and several of the Allied powers declared it void.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Nevertheless, the formal treaty later concluded and confirmed on 27 November was essentially a ratification of Napier's original, and his friend Lord Palmerston congratulated Napier.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] In acknowledgement of his distinguished services during the campaign, Napier was knighted as a KCB on 4 December 1840, and was also included in the vote of thanks by the Houses of Parliament.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He was also presented by the Emperors of Russia and Austria and the King of Prussia with the Order of St.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] George of Russia; the Order of Maria Theresa of Austria; and the Red Eagle of Prussia.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] In January 1841, Napier carried out a special mission to Alexandria and Cairo to see that the treaty was being adhered to before returning to Britain in March.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He was invited to stand as Parliamentary candidate in two constituencies and so at his own request was placed on half pay.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He was returned as Liberal Party MP for Marylebone at the 1841 general election.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He spoke mainly on naval topics, especially conditions for seamen and increasing the strength of the navy.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] In April 1842, with 67 other MPs, he voted for the motion of William Sharman Crawford to form a committee to consider the demands of the People's Charter (1838): votes for working men, protected by secret ballot.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] In November 1841, Napier was appointed Naval Aide-de-Camp to Queen Victoria.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He subsequently wrote and published *War in Syria*, his personal account of the campaign.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] On 4 December 1845 he was invested with the Freedom of the City of Edinburgh.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Napier continued to be interested in warship design and was responsible for the design of the paddle-frigate *Sidon* launched in May 1846.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] In the same year he was promoted rear-admiral of the Blue on 9 November. in May 1847 he was appointed to the command of the Channel Fleet, hoisting his flag in HMS *St Vincent*.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] By this time he was perhaps the naval personality most famous to the general public: his level of everyday name-recognition is shown by the passing allusion in William Makepeace Thackeray's famous humorous ballad *Little Billee* ("the British fleet a-riding at anchor / with Admiral Napier, K.C.B.").
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He did not stand again for his parliamentary seat at Marylebone in the July–August 1847 general election.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] The Channel Fleet was sometimes a sinecure, but this was by no means the case during Napier's period of command.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] The fleet's area of operations was not just the English Channel but more or less throughout what in the 20th century would be called the Western Approaches.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Portugal was in the closing stages of its 'little' civil war, the Patuleia, and British interests in that country needed protecting.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Ireland, in the aftermath of the Great Famine, was feared to be near insurrection.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Moreover, there were considerations of experiment and training with new ships, made necessary by the rapid technological advances such as screw propulsion.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] During 1848, the fleet was mainly off the coast of Ireland, where the political situation dictated that Napier show the flag and train for the eventuality of transporting and landing soldiers on practically any part of the Irish coast.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] In December he took the Channel Fleet further than it had ever operated before, when it was sent to Gibraltar and then onto the Moroccan coast, with the purpose of curbing the activities of Rif pirates.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He compelled the Sultan of Morocco, Muley Abderrahman, to grant compensation for the injuries he had inflicted on British commerce.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Napier returned to Britain in April 1849 and was ordered to strike his flag.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] His disappointment that his expected three years term had been cut short led to bitter letters to *The Times* criticising the Admiralty's policy.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] When he applied for the vacant Mediterranean command, the Government and Admiralty agreed that he could not be trusted and he was rejected, Rear-Admiral Sir James Dundas being appointed instead.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] This led Napier to write more angry letters to the newspapers and directly to Prime Minister Lord John Russell claiming that he had been defrauded of his just rights.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He unsuccessfully contested the parliamentary seat for the Borough of Lambeth at a by-election on 7 August 1850.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] On 28 May 1853 he was promoted to vice-admiral of the Blue.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] At the outbreak of the Crimean War, Napier received the command of the Baltic Fleet, the largest fleet which the Royal Navy had assembled since the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] This was not without misgivings on the part of the Admiralty, but he was the most senior and experienced officer available.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Napier hoisted his flag in February 1854 in the steam ship of the line *Duke of Wellington*, his subordinate commanders being the rear-admirals Armar Lowry Corry, second in command, Henry Ducie Chads, third in command, and James Hanway Plumridge, commanding the scouting forces.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] They were all elderly men, at most a year or so younger than Napier himself.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Napier's force, which was augmented in June by a French fleet sent by Napoleon III and commanded by Alexandre Ferdinand Parseval-Deschenes, though impressive on paper, was radically unsuited to operations in the Baltic Sea and chronically short of men and especially of experienced seamen.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He was also hampered by contradictory sets of orders from the Admiralty.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Nevertheless, he successfully blockaded all the Russian ports, sufficiently overawed the Russian Baltic Fleet that it never stirred from its moorings, and carried out many bombardment operations as far as the northernmost point of the Gulf of Finland.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] During the campaign the first ever Victoria Cross was won by midshipman Charles Davis Lucas of the gunboat *Hecla*, who threw a Russian explosive shell overboard before it could detonate.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] During the campaign Rear-Admiral Corry was invalided home because of poor health; he was replaced by Commodore (later Rear-Admiral) Henry Byam Martin.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] His inaction was thoroughly justified by the sequel: in 1855 a better-equipped Anglo-French fleet did bombard Sveaborg, but despite an enormous expenditure of ammunition caused the fortress only trifling structural damage.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Napier felt he was continually being second-guessed by the Admiralty, and especially by the First Lord of the Admiralty, Sir James Graham.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Never one to mince his words or submit to what he felt to be unmerited criticism, Napier's 'disrespectful' tone in his despatches, which the Admiralty complained of, sealed his professional fate.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Nevertheless, though lacking any dramatic action apart from the capture of Bomarsund, Napier had achieved a great deal.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] In one modern assessment, the campaign "had successfully bottled up the Russian Navy for the entire first summer of the war.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] The tsar had been denied an opportunity to reinforce his Black Sea fleet with additional ships.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] The 30,000 Russian troops posted in the Gulf had also been prevented from joining the army in the Crimea." Napier's constant training welded the fleet personnel into a much more competent force for the next year's campaign, and not a single ship was lost.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] On Napier's return from the Baltic to Britain in December 1854 he was ordered to haul down his flag and informed his command was terminated, the fleet being given for the campaign of 1855 to Admiral the Hon.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Richard Saunders Dundas, the Second Sea Lord.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] None of the flag officers of the 1854 campaign was allowed to return to the Baltic in 1855, but Sir Michael Seymour, Napier's Captain of the Fleet, was promoted to rear-admiral and was made second-in-command to Dundas.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Nevertheless, some of the leading seamen in the fleet, such as Captain (later Admiral) Sir Bartholomew Sulivan, maintained along with him that Napier's strategy had been wise and the faults lay with the Admiralty themselves.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] After the war the Russians testified that, knowing Napier's reputation, their main hope had been of his making a foolhardy attack on their fleet under the guns of Kronstadt, where they were confident he would have come to grief.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Napier was elected MP for Southwark in February 1855, and carried his dispute with the Admiralty to the floor of the House of Commons.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He continued to campaign vigorously for improvements in the way common seamen were treated during and after service, and maintained his parliamentary seat, though broken in health, until his death on 6 November 1860.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] His tomb is in the churchyard of All Saints, Catherington in Hampshire.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] The ships of the Portuguese Navy went into eight days of mourning for their former commander.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] Just before his death Napier had hoped to persuade Giuseppe Garibaldi to acquire a fleet for the liberation of Italy, which he would have commanded.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] According to the *Encyclopædia Britannica* entry of 1911, "Sir Charles Napier was a man of undoubted energy and courage, but of no less eccentricity and vanity.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] His common nickname in the Navy was 'Black Charlie' because of his swarthy appearance and dark side-whiskers.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] He was also known as 'Mad Charlie' because of his eccentric behaviour and enthusiasms, and 'Dirty Charlie' from his habit of wearing the most unsuitable and ill-fitting clothes while insisting that his officers were correctly dressed at all times.
[src:aaron-manby/charles-napier-royal-navy-officer] There is a memorial to him within St Paul's Cathedral.
[src:aaron-manby/charlotte-dundas] Development of experimental steam engined paddle boats by William Symington had halted when the sponsor, Patrick Miller of Dalswinton, abandoned the project.
[src:aaron-manby/charlotte-dundas] Symington had continued building steam pumping engines and mill engines.
[src:aaron-manby/charlotte-dundas] In 1793 he had developed a drive using a pivoted crosshead beam above the vertical cylinder to transmit power to a crank.
[src:aaron-manby/charlotte-dundas] The boat was built by Alexander Hart at Grangemouth to Symington's design with a vertical cylinder engine and crosshead transmitting power to a crank driving the paddlewheels.
[src:aaron-manby/charlotte-dundas] Trials on the River Carron in June 1801 were successful.
[src:aaron-manby/charlotte-dundas] This first boat may have been named *Charlotte Dundas* and the trials apparently included towing sloops from the river Forth up the Carron and thence along the Forth and Clyde Canal.
[src:aaron-manby/charlotte-dundas] There was concern about wave damage to the canal banks, and possibly the boat was found to be underpowered on the canal, so the canal company refused further trials.
[src:aaron-manby/charlotte-dundas] In 1801 Symington patented a horizontal steam engine directly linked to a crank, and got the support of Lord Dundas for a second steamboat which would become famous as *Charlotte Dundas*, named in honour of his Lordship's daughter.
[src:aaron-manby/charlotte-dundas] Symington designed a new hull around his powerful horizontal engine, with the crank driving a large paddle wheel in a central upstand in the hull, aimed at avoiding damage to the canal banks.
[src:aaron-manby/charlotte-dundas] The new boat was 56 ft (17.1 m) long, 18 ft (5.5 m) wide and 8 ft (2.4 m) depth, with a wooden hull.
[src:aaron-manby/charlotte-dundas] After a model of the boat was made and shown to Lord Dundas, the boat was built by John Allan, and the engine by the Carron Company.
[src:aaron-manby/charlotte-dundas] The first sailing was on the canal in Glasgow on 4 January 1803, with Lord Dundas and a few of his relatives and friends on board.
[src:aaron-manby/charlotte-dundas] This demonstrated the practicality of steam power for towing boats.
[src:aaron-manby/charlotte-dundas] Plans to introduce boats on the Forth and Clyde canal were thwarted, largely by fears of erosion of the banks, and a project to build tug boats for the Bridgewater Canal had ended with the Duke of Bridgewater's death a few days before the March trial.
[src:aaron-manby/charlotte-dundas] *Charlotte Dundas* was left in a backwater of the canal at Bainsford until it was broken up in 1861.
[src:aaron-manby/charlotte-dundas] Symington was not paid all he had invested in construction of *Charlotte Dundas* and was left disappointed, but the development of steamboats was continued by others including Robert Fulton in the United States and Henry Bell in Scotland.
